        <!-- SEO Content -->
        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>How to Calculate Your Take-Home Pay</h2>
            <p>Your <strong>take-home pay</strong> (also called net pay) is the amount you actually receive after all taxes and deductions are subtracted from your gross salary. Understanding the difference between your gross pay and net pay is essential for budgeting, negotiating salaries, and making informed financial decisions.</p>
            <p>This paycheck calculator walks through every step of the process: starting with your gross income, applying the 2026 federal tax brackets based on your filing status, calculating FICA taxes (Social Security and Medicare), applying your state's income tax rate, and subtracting pre-tax deductions like 401(k) contributions and health insurance premiums.</p>

            <h2>Understanding Federal Income Tax Brackets (2026)</h2>
            <p>The US federal income tax system is <strong>progressive</strong>, meaning higher portions of your income are taxed at higher rates. For 2026, single filers face seven brackets: 10% on the first $11,925 of taxable income, 12% up to $48,475, 22% up to $103,350, 24% up to $197,300, 32% up to $250,525, 35% up to $626,350, and 37% on income exceeding $626,350.</p>
            <p>Before applying these brackets, your income is reduced by the <strong>standard deduction</strong> — $15,000 for single filers, $30,000 for married filing jointly, and $22,500 for head of household in 2026. This means a single filer earning $75,000 only pays federal tax on $60,000 of taxable income, resulting in an effective rate much lower than the 22% marginal bracket.</p>

            <h2>FICA Taxes: Social Security and Medicare</h2>
            <p>FICA taxes fund Social Security and Medicare. <strong>Social Security tax</strong> is 6.2% on income up to $176,600 (the 2026 wage base limit). <strong>Medicare tax</strong> is 1.45% on all income, plus an additional 0.9% surtax on income exceeding $200,000 for single filers. Together, most workers pay 7.65% of their income in FICA taxes. Unlike income tax, there is no standard deduction for FICA — it applies to every dollar of gross wages.</p>

            <h2>How State Income Tax Affects Your Paycheck</h2>
            <p>State income taxes vary dramatically across the US. Nine states — Alaska, Florida, Nevada, New Hampshire, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington, and Wyoming — charge no state income tax on wages. On the other end, states like California, Oregon, Minnesota, and New Jersey have top rates exceeding 9%. This calculator uses simplified flat effective rates by state to give you a quick estimate. For the most precise calculation, consult your state's specific brackets and deductions.</p>

            <h2>Pre-Tax Deductions and Their Impact</h2>
            <p><strong>Pre-tax deductions</strong> like 401(k) contributions and health insurance premiums reduce your taxable income before federal and state taxes are calculated. This creates a tax advantage: every dollar you contribute pre-tax saves you money equal to your marginal tax rate. For example, if you're in the 22% federal bracket and contribute $500/month to your 401(k), you save $110/month in federal taxes — so the actual reduction to your take-home pay is only $390, not $500.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <div class="faq-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I calculate my take-home pay?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">To calculate take-home pay, start with your gross salary and subtract federal income tax (based on your tax bracket and filing status), state income tax, Social Security tax (6.2% up to $176,600 in 2026), Medicare tax (1.45% plus 0.9% on income over $200K), and any pre-tax deductions like 401(k) contributions and health insurance premiums. The remainder is your net pay or take-home pay.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the difference between gross pay and net pay?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Gross pay is your total earnings before any deductions — it's the salary or hourly rate stated in your employment offer. Net pay (take-home pay) is what you actually receive after federal taxes, state taxes, FICA taxes (Social Security and Medicare), and pre-tax deductions are subtracted. Typically, net pay is 60–75% of gross pay depending on your tax bracket and deductions.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How much of my paycheck goes to federal taxes?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Federal income tax uses a progressive bracket system. For 2026, a single filer pays 10% on the first $11,925, 12% on income up to $48,475, 22% on income up to $103,350, 24% up to $197,300, 32% up to $250,525, 35% up to $626,350, and 37% on income above that. Your effective federal tax rate depends on your total taxable income after deductions, and is usually lower than your marginal bracket.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What are FICA taxes and how much do I pay?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">FICA stands for Federal Insurance Contributions Act and includes Social Security tax (6.2% on income up to $176,600 in 2026) and Medicare tax (1.45% on all income, plus an additional 0.9% on income over $200,000). Combined, most workers pay 7.65% in FICA taxes. Your employer also pays a matching 7.65%, but that doesn't come from your paycheck.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Which US states have no income tax?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Nine US states have no state income tax: Alaska, Florida, Nevada, New Hampshire, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington, and Wyoming. New Hampshire and Washington do tax certain investment or capital gains income but not wages. Living in a no-income-tax state can significantly increase your take-home pay compared to high-tax states like California (up to 13.3%) or New York (up to 10.9%).</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do pre-tax deductions like 401(k) affect my paycheck?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Pre-tax deductions like 401(k) contributions and health insurance premiums are subtracted from your gross pay before income taxes are calculated. This lowers your taxable income and reduces the amount of federal and state tax you owe. For example, contributing $500/month to a 401(k) in the 22% bracket saves you about $110/month in federal taxes, so the actual cost to your take-home pay is only about $390.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How often do I get paid and does pay frequency matter?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Common pay frequencies are weekly (52 paychecks/year), biweekly (26 paychecks), semi-monthly (24 paychecks), and monthly (12 paychecks). Your annual salary stays the same regardless of frequency, but each individual paycheck amount differs. Biweekly is most common in the US. Note that biweekly pay results in two months per year with three paychecks, which can help with budgeting or extra debt payments.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is my effective tax rate vs marginal tax rate?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Your marginal tax rate is the rate applied to your last dollar of income — it's your highest tax bracket. Your effective tax rate is the average rate you actually pay across all brackets, calculated as total tax divided by total income. For example, a single filer earning $80,000 in 2026 has a marginal rate of 22% but an effective federal rate of about 13.5%. The effective rate is more useful for understanding your true tax burden.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I calculate my hourly rate from my salary?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">To convert an annual salary to an hourly rate, divide by the number of work hours per year. For a standard full-time schedule of 40 hours/week and 52 weeks/year, that's 2,080 hours. So a $75,000 salary equals about $36.06/hour. For take-home hourly rate, divide your annual net pay by 2,080 instead. This calculator shows both gross and net amounts per pay period to help you understand your true hourly earnings.</div>
            </div>
        </div>

